#------------ SCATTERPLOT -------------
colorPlotFunc <- function(ds=dataset, collection) {
  plot(
    x = ds,
    col = as.integer(collection)
  )
}
simplePlotFunc <- function(xVar, yVar) {
  plot(
    x = xVar,
    y = yVar
  )
}

#------------ CORRELATION -------------
fnVisualizeCorrelation <- function(corData, param = "") {
  if (param == ""){
    corrplot(corData, order = "AOE", title = "Correlation Plot")
  } else {
    corrplot(corData, order = "AOE", method = param, title = "Correlation Plot")
  }
}


#------------ DECISION TREE -------------
treeFunc <- function(rfModel, treeNum) {
  # get tree by index
  tree <-
    randomForest::getTree(rfModel, k = treeNum, labelVar = TRUE) %>%
    tibble::rownames_to_column() %>%
    # make leaf split points to NA, so the 0s won't get plotted
    mutate(`split point` = ifelse(is.na(prediction), `split point`, NA))
  
  # prepare data frame for graph
  graph_frame <- data.frame(
    from = rep(tree$rowname, 2),
    to = c(tree$`left daughter`, tree$`right daughter`)
  )
  
  # convert to graph and delete the last node that we don't want to plot
  graph <- graph_from_data_frame(graph_frame) %>%
    delete_vertices("0")
  
  # set node labels
  V(graph)$node_label <-
    gsub("_", " ", as.character(tree$`split var`))
  V(graph)$leaf_label <- as.character(tree$prediction)
  V(graph)$split <-
    as.character(round(tree$`split point`, digits = 2))
  
  # plot
  plot <- ggraph(graph, 'dendrogram') +
    theme_bw() +
    geom_edge_link() +
    geom_node_point() +
    geom_node_text(aes(label = node_label), na.rm = TRUE, repel = TRUE) +
    geom_node_label(aes(label = split),
                    vjust = 2.5,
                    na.rm = TRUE,
                    fill = "white") +
    geom_node_label(
      aes(label = leaf_label, fill = leaf_label),
      na.rm = TRUE,
      repel = TRUE,
      colour = "white",
      fontface = "bold",
      show.legend = FALSE
    ) +
    theme(
      panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
      panel.grid.major = element_blank(),
      panel.background = element_blank(),
      plot.background = element_rect(fill = "white"),
      panel.border = element_blank(),
      axis.line = element_blank(),
      axis.text.x = element_blank(),
      axis.text.y = element_blank(),
      axis.ticks = element_blank(),
      axis.title.x = element_blank(),
      axis.title.y = element_blank(),
      plot.title = element_text(size = 18)
    )
  
  print(plot)
}

# create "file selector" list from an s3 location
# can (someday?) pass alternative s3 folders, filename filters
def get_s3_filenames( s3_loc=None ):
    
    import subprocess
    import re
    import os
    
    # in the future, replace with call to `aw.store.uri`
    s3_endpoint = "s3://{d[0]}/{d[1]}/source/".format(
        d=[os.environ[x] for x in ['AW_S3_STORAGE_BUCKET','AW_S3_STORAGE_KEY']]
    )
    # s3_endpoint = s3_root + '/' + folder + '/'
    # if s3_loc is None:
    #     # s3_endpoint = aw.store.uri + '/source/'
    #     awstore.uri = 's3://dmp-dmp20-int-fico-pto-tenant/solutioninstances/27r6giebhf'
    #     s3_endpoint = aw.store.uri + '/source/'
    # else:
    ## sadly for %python, we have to hard-code the S3 bucket...here are some common values:
    # s3_endpoint = 's3://dmp-dmp20-int-fico-field-tenant/solutioninstances/gv9db380ed/source/'  # FIELD INT
    # s3_endpoint = 's3://dmp-dmp20-ort-fico-pto-tenant/solutioninstances/6ntu5lwpuw/source/'    # PTO ORT
    # s3_endpoint = 's3://dmp-dmp20-int-fico-pto-tenant/solutioninstances/27r6giebhf/source/'    # PTO INT
    # s3_endpoint = 's3://dmp-dmp20-dev-fico-pto-tenant/solutioninstances/14hv2pjrd87/source/'   # PTO DEV

    my_sets = []
     
    all_objs = subprocess.check_output(['aws', 's3', 'ls', s3_endpoint]).decode("utf-8")
    
    # process the aws/s3/ls output
    for line in all_objs.splitlines():
        my_keys = ['date', 'time', 'size', 'filename']
        my_data = re.split(r'\s{1,}', str(line), len(my_keys)-1)
        # build entry when we have all the expected data
        if(len(my_keys) == len(my_data)):
            s3_entry = dict(zip(my_keys, my_data))
            if(s3_entry['filename'] != ".bucket"):
                s3_entry['size'] = int(s3_entry['size']) // 1024
                my_sets.append(s3_entry)
     
    # sort entries by alpha, ignoring case:
    my_sets.sort(key=lambda x: x['filename'].lower())
    
    # as a return from the z.select, I want the simple name, from this list:
    my_names = [x['filename'] for x in my_sets]
     
    # but as a description in the pulldown, I want to show my user this:
    my_descripts = ['{filename} - ({size:10,d} kb, time="{date} {time}")'.format(**x) for x in my_sets]
     
    # build a list of length-2 tuples for (filename, file description)
    selection_list = list(zip( my_names, my_descripts ))
    
    # return the s3 prefix and the selection list
    return (s3_endpoint, selection_list)


# divide an endpoint into its bucket and key prefix
# expects an input of the form 's3://some_bucket/arbitrary/extra/path/names/'
def get_s3_parts(s3_endpoint):
    import re
    # per AWS docs, bucket address should match: # "^[a-zA-Z0-9.\-_]{1,255}$"
    # (this regular expression is far less precise)
    my_pattern = r"s3://([^\/]+)/(.*)"
    my_match = re.match( my_pattern, s3_endpoint )
    if my_match:
        return (my_match.groups())
    else:
        print("Sorry, cannot make sense of '{}'".format(s3_endpoint))
        return None


# given a simple filename and a partial s3 address, return a stream of bytes
def get_s3_file( s3_endpoint, filename ):
    import io, boto3
    from botocore.client import Config
    from gzip import GzipFile
    # from bz2 import BZ2File

    # ensure the connection is authorized using sig4 key
    s3 = boto3.client('s3', config=Config(signature_version='s3v4'))
    (my_bucket, my_prefix) = get_s3_parts(s3_endpoint)
    my_key = my_prefix + filename
    try:
        obj = s3.get_object(Bucket=my_bucket, Key=my_key)
    except:
        # (greater precision in this exception handling would be nice)
        print("Cannot access '{}' from '{}'".format(my_key, my_bucket))
        return None
    else:
        # return the body of the s3 object, accounting for compression
        if my_key.endswith('.gz'):
            bytestream = io.BytesIO(obj['Body'].read())
            file_loc = GzipFile(None, 'rb', fileobj=bytestream)#.read()#.decode('utf-8')
        elif my_key.endswith('.bz2'):
            # file_loc = BZ2File(io.BytesIO(obj['Body'].read()), mode='rb')
            #### close, but fails with this message:
            #### TypeError: coercing to Unicode: need string or buffer, _io.BytesIO found
            # file_loc = None
            #### I give up, just copy the file locally so Pandas can read it
            file_loc = "/mnt/tmp/" + filename
            s3.download_file(my_bucket, my_key, file_loc)
            #
            # many failed attempts...
            # bytestream = io.BytesIO(obj['Body'].read())
            # file_loc = bytestream
            # file_loc = BZ2File(None, 'rb', fileobj=bytestream)#.read()#.decode('utf-8')
            # file_loc = BZ2File(bytestream, mode='rb')#.read()#.decode('utf-8')
            # file_loc = BZ2File(bytestream, mode='rb').read().decode('utf-8')
            # file_loc = BZ2File(bytestream, mode='rb').decode('utf-8')
        else:
            file_loc = io.BytesIO(obj['Body'].read())
        return file_loc


def parcel_dataframe(in_df, agb_col_name, inf_prob_col_name, sample_wt_col_name = None):
    """
    Perform parceling of the given dataframe.

    :param in_df:   Input dataframe
    :param agb_col_name:    Name of the AGB column name
    :param inf_prob_col_name:   Name of the inference probability column
    :param sample_wt_col_name:  Sample weight column (optional)

    :return: Returns a parceled dataframe with the same column schema.
    """
    
    import numpy as np
    import pandas as pd
    
    # Disable the SettingwithCopyWarning which is misleading and will not affect this function
    # https://www.dataquest.io/blog/settingwithcopywarning/
    orig_opt = pd.get_option('mode.chained_assignment')
    pd.set_option('mode.chained_assignment', None)

    # Partition the dataset into parceling candidates and others
    p_df = in_df.loc[(in_df[agb_col_name] < 1) & (in_df[agb_col_name] > 0), :]  # parceling candidates
    o_df = in_df.loc[~((in_df[agb_col_name] < 1) & (in_df[agb_col_name] > 0)), :]  # others

    # Add new columns for 'AGB'. Initialize it with 0.
    p_df['New_AGB'] = 0

    # Add new columns for 'New AGB Probability'.
    # Initialize it given inference probability.
    p_df['New_Pr_AGB'] = p_df[inf_prob_col_name]

    # Set New_AGB to 1 where the 'AGB' is a float value greater or equals 0.5
    p_df.loc[(p_df[agb_col_name] >= 0.5), 'New_AGB'] = 1

    # Reset the indices
    p_df.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)

    # Make a copy of the parceling candidates for creating the
    # duplicate rows
    p_df1 = p_df.copy()

    # Reverse the target label for the New_AGB
    p_df1.loc[:, 'New_AGB'] = np.where(p_df1['New_AGB'] == 1, 0, 1)

    # Set the probability New_Pr_AGB for these rows
    p_df1.loc[:, 'New_Pr_AGB'] = 1 - p_df1['New_Pr_AGB']

    # We do this to place the orginal row and the duplicate row
    # next to each other
    new_p_df = pd.concat([p_df, p_df1]).sort_index(kind='merge')

    del p_df, p_df1

    # Drop the rows where 'New_Pr_AGB' is zero
    new_p_df.query('New_Pr_AGB != 0', inplace=True)

    # Update the sample weights with the new probability
    if sample_wt_col_name is not None:
        new_p_df[sample_wt_col_name] = new_p_df[sample_wt_col_name] * new_p_df['New_Pr_AGB']

    new_p_df[agb_col_name] = new_p_df['New_AGB']
    new_p_df[inf_prob_col_name] = new_p_df['New_Pr_AGB']
    new_p_df.drop(['New_AGB', 'New_Pr_AGB'], axis=1, inplace=True)

    # At this point we have completed parceling. Next append to the rest of the rows.

    final_df = new_p_df.append(o_df)
    final_df.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)

    del new_p_df

    pd.set_option('mode.chained_assignment', orig_opt)
    return final_df

pdNormalized = pd.DataFrame(preprocessing.scale(pdDataset[arrSelHeaders[1:]]))
